<DOC><DOCNO> AP890510-0150 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1523EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Swiss-Money     05-10 0230</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Swiss-Money,0237</SECOND><HEAD>Government Proposes Legislation Against Money-Laundering</HEAD><DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government Wednesday announceddraft legislation that would make money-laundering a crime.   The proposal, expected to be presented to Parliament beforemid-June, is aimed at combatting drug-trafficking and organizedcrime, said Justice Minister Arnold Koller.   Switzerland's financial and political communities have beenrocked by the ``Lebanon Connection'' scandal in which investigatorssay about $1.2 billion, including alleged drug money, was recycledthrough Swiss banks.   The case led to the resignation of the former justice minister,Elizabeth Kopp, after it was revealed she tipped off her husband tosever his links with Shakarchi Trading, a Lebanese-controlled,Zurich-based company under investigation.   The legislation would outlaw those acts that obstruct theinvestigation of the ``origin, the tracing, or the seizure'' ofassets known to have come from illegal activities.   Violators would be punished by up to five years in prison and afine of up to $600,000.   A second part of the proposed law would punish bankers, lawyers,financial advisers and banknote traders for lack of care if theyfail to determine the identity of their customers in transactions.Offenders face up to a year in prison.   The draft law was greeted by three of the four parties making upthe government coalition and was cautiously welcomed by the banks.The Social Democratic Party said it did not go far enough.</TEXT></DOC>